<font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial">
Let's end this thread shall we. It's a pointless debate unless new evidence is being introduced. And I have seen none in this thread. Nothing being argued over now hasn't been done at least a hundread times before in other threads. <P>Tunzell, excepting some trolls, most people who favor AC/HP do not think cha has no effect on mez and charms. They only think cha has a negligeable effect on mez and charms.<P>From all the tests that I have seen, there is at most a 5% greater chance in succeeding in mezzing a mob which originally resisted the initial rolls on whether it is mezzed or not. Now for me personally, I feel 5% is not enough for me to concentrate on any cha gear. Like Llorian said, most enchanters 55+ are at least 130cha or higher simply by accident. I am at 220-230'ish cha buffed simply from the gear I wear, none of which are for it's cha although many do have cha on it.<P>Now, as I said, it's generally accepted that high cha will raise your chances of getting a successful mez by roughly 5%. Let me post a few theoretical situations and let's see how they turn out. For all examples, let's pretend the mezzer is level 50. Let's also say the echanter is mezzing an average of 1 mob per minute. And that groups lasted 10 hours. We'll also pretend the random number generator does not exhist.<P>Example 1: Mezzer is only mezzing mobs that are 5+ levels below him with average to low magic resist (lguk, solb). In this case, there is only roughly a 5% chance of resists since everything is easily mezzed. In this case person "a" with low cha will have maybe 30 mobs resisted per hour (60 mobs per hour times 10 hours times 5% chance of resist). 60 x 10 x 5% = 30 mobs resisting mez per hour. Person "b" has high cha and consequently has a 5% higher chance of successfully mezzing those mobs who have failed the initial checks for whether mez lands or not. Remember, cha only comes into play when the initial checks for level and magic resist have failed. Thus the person with high cha will only hav 28 resists in that 10 hour span. 30 mobs x 5% = 1.5 mobs successfully mezzed due to cha saves. So 30 - 1.5 = 28.5 mobs. So in that 10 hour span you mezzed 1.5 mobs more than someone with low cha and rounding that off it's 30 mobs resisting mez for low cha and 28 mobs resisting mez for high cha.<P>Example 2: Mezzer is mezzing mobs 5+ levels below himself again but with high magic resist. Assuming due to magic resist, in this sitation there is a 10% chance of resist before cha is factored in. Person "a" with low resist will of course have 60 mobs resist mez in a 10 hour spawn. Person "b" will have an extra 3 mobs mezzed due to high cha. (60 x 5%) - 60 = 57. So instead of having 60 mobs resisting mez for low cha you have 57 mobs resisting mez for high cha.<P>Situation 3: Mezzer is mezzing mobs that are +/- 2 levels of him with average to low magic resists. Due to levels mobs now have a 15% chance of resisting mez. 600 x 15% = 90 mobs resisting mez in a 10 hour span for person "a" with low cha. Person "b" with a high cha (90 x 5% = 4.5) will have 85.5 mobs resisting mez. So with a high cha person will only mez about 5 more mobs in that situation as compared to the low cha person.<P>Situtation 4: Mezzer is mezzing mobs that are +/= 2 levels of him and the mobs have high magic resists. Assuming with the higher magic resist, mez failures are at about 25%. So, 600 x 25% = 150 resists in a 10 hour span for person "a" with low cha. Person "b" with high cha will have 7.5 less mobs resisted due to high cha. Rounding numbers off again, that's 150 resists for low cha versus 142 resists for high cha. <P><BR>In these scenarious, while cha will help, the effect is not enough for you to go all out on cha. I think these theoretical situations I described are pretty indicative of what you'll see in the game while playing. Those were scenarious I thought out when deciding whether I would keep high cha or chuck it for some ac/hp gear. I did not list situations for when you are trying to mez red con mobs because you'll have an insane time trying to mez them regardless of your cha. If you're mezzing mobs with such a high magic resist that you are getting a greater than 25% chance of resist then it's not worth going to unless there is some insanely good gear in those areas or you're raiding. Note how much of Velious was completely empty except for raids when Velious first came out because magic resist was so high that no matter what you raised your cha to you were not going to be able to mez without the cleric spending half his mana on you. People will not go to zones with significantly high resists when there are zones with lower mob resists around. Velk's Lab used to be completely empty when Velious first came out because level 60 enchanters were having trouble mezzing the spiders on the bottom floor much less try to mez mobs in the upper or lower kobold camps. I think my 4 examples covers 85% of the situations in which an enchanter will go through when grinding for xp and general dungeon crawling.  Keeping that in mind, my conclusion is that sacrificing cha for ac/hp gear is much more useful to me.<br /><br />--------------------<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=296873" target="_blank">Hikaru's Magelo Profile</a><br />
</font>
